    <stitle>FE 300 BUS BODY COMPONENTS - Body Accessories and Miscellaneous - Windshield Wipers and Washer System
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="6">
        <title>Windshield Wipers and Washer System</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>This section covers the servicing, removal and installation of the windshield wiper system. The
                windshield wiper system is an independent dual system. Each wiper is controlled by a separate switch.
                the wiper motor operates with a dynamic or power park sweep motion when the system is turned "OFF". Each
                wiper has two speeds unless equipped with a delay wiper control (optional equipment).
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Adjustment</title>
            <para>Each windshield wiper system is properly adjusted at the factory. Due to adverse conditions and normal
                wear, minor adjustments may be required. To adjust blade angle, loosen mounting screws and drive thrust
                nut, pivot into position and retighten.
            </para>
            <figure id="f47003214" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g47003214.webp" filename="../figg47/G47003214.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                         scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 214. Position of Arm</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">ADJUSTING SLOT</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">MOUNTING SCREW</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">DRIVE THRUST NUT</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">MOUNTING SCREW</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Sweep Pattern Adjustment</title>
            <para>If the sweep pattern of the windshield wiper arm or blades appear to be out of synch, operate the
                system to determine if a slight adjustment will resolve the problem. For example, if the wiper blade is
                hitting the lower windshield gasket rubber, a slight adjustment may resolve the problem. Use the steps
                described below to correct the sweep pattern.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Operate the windshield wiper system in both dry and wet conditions using both high and
                    low speeds.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect the sweep pattern in all conditions listed above for contact with the windshield
                    rubber gasket. If no contact is made, continue to step 3. If no contact is made, check for worn
                    windshield wiper blades.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position the windshield wiper arm as shown in Figure 214. Then cycle the wiper arm to
                    the "OFF" position, allowing the wiper to park.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position the wiper arm and blade on its natural laying surface.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pivot the wiper arm knuckle as shown in Figure 215</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Arm installation directions</para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Install drive arm in disengaged position.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Slide knuckle of arm onto knurled cylinder.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Rotate locking lever into "locked" position.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Move arm into engaged position (blade against glass).</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>To remove reverse steps 1-4.</para>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f47003215" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g47003215.webp" filename="../figg47/G47003215.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                         scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 215. Pivot Knuckle</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">DISENGAGED</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">ENGAGED</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">LOCKING LEVER</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">UNLOCKED</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">LOCKED</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the mounting hardware on both shafts as shown in Figure 216</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f47003216" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="g47003216.webp" filename="../figg47/G47003216.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                         scalefitwidth="502px" scalefitheight="432px"/>
                <caption>Figure 216. Remove Hardware</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">WIPER MOTOR</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">FLAT WASHER</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">GASKET</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">SLAVE SHAFT ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">WASHER</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">BOLT</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">WIPER ARM</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">LOCK WASHER</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">CAP NUT</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">RETAINER</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">SPLINE</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">RUBBER BOOT</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">NUT</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">BUSHING</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">WASHER HEAD</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">FLAT WASHER</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">NUT-WASHER HEAD</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Windshield Wiper Motor Location</title>
            <para>The windshield wiper motor is located behind the front access panel (
                <hotlnk document="s47003_5.xml" xrefid="f4700306">Figure 6, Item 13</hotlnk>). Access may be gained by
                releasing the panel latch and opening the service panel.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Windshield Washer System</title>
            <para>The windshield washer system reservoir is located on the driver (street ) side of the bus below the
                electrical compartment (
                <hotlnk document="s47003_6.xml" xrefid="f4700333">Figure 33, Item 3</hotlnk>). The windshield washer
                reservoir may be a skirt mounted or frame mounted assembly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f47003217" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g47003217.webp" filename="../figg47/G47003217.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                         scalefitwidth="280px" scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 217. Windshield Reservoir Frame Mounted</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">FRAME RAIL</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">LOCK WASHER</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">NUT</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">WASHER SUPPLY PUMP</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">RESERVOIR MOUNTING BOLTS</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">RESERVOIR</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">RESERVOIR CAP</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f47003218" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g47003218.webp" filename="../figg47/G47003218.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
